<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,1554,2013]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1734,1760]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species is easily be recognized by its light-grey forewing with brown veins mottled with black, and its mostly black palpomere 2 of the labial palpus. This wing pattern is unique among Afrotropical species of 
<emphasis box="[235,379,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Huemer &amp; Karsholt" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[235,374,1807,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Scrobipalpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scrobipalpa</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Male genitalia characters that separate 
<taxonomicName authority="Bidzilya, 2021" authorityName="Bidzilya" authorityYear="2021" box="[830,941,1807,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Scrobipalpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="staudei" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[830,941,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">S. staudei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[949,1041,1807,1833]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[949,1041,1807,1833]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
from other species of Afrotropical 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Huemer &amp; Karsholt" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[151,287,1843,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Scrobipalpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,287,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Scrobipalpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are a broad uncus, a comparatively broad sacculus, and a short vincular process, in combination with a broad saccus and a sigmoidal valva.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="25" lastPageNumber="26" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,1554,2013]" lastBlockId="25.[151,1437,151,789]" lastPageId="25" lastPageNumber="26" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,419,1914,1940]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Description. Adult</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[435,519,1914,1941]" captionStart="FIGURES 51–60" captionStartId="53.[151,264,1792,1816]" captionTargetBox="[298,1288,181,1760]" captionTargetId="figure-16@53.[298,1288,181,1768]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURES 51–60. Scrobipalpa spp., adults. 51. S. staudei sp. nov., South Africa, Magaliesburg, HT, male (gen. slide 3/19, OB). 52–54. S. obsoletella, South Africa. 52. Vredental, female (gen. slide 37/13, OB). 53. Vredental, male, HT of hospes (gen. slide K. Sattler 287a). 54. South Africa, Port Elizabeth, male, HT of xylochroa. 55. S. afromontana sp. nov., Kenya, Rutundu Track, HT, male (gen. slide DJLA 1419). 56. S. erexita sp. nov., South Africa, 50 km NE Bitterfontein, HT, female (gen. slide 154/17, OB). 57, 58. S. admirabilis sp. nov., Namibia, Fischriver, Gondwana Canyon Lodge. 57. HT, male (gen. slide 317/20, OB). 58. PT, male (gen. slide 164/12, OB). 59, 60. S. griseata sp. nov., South Africa, Petersburg. 59. HT, male (gen. slide 15/13, OB). 60. PT, male. Scale bar = wingspan." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5712547" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5712547/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 
<quantity box="[660,784,1914,1941]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" unit="mm" value="15.5" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="15.0">15–16 mm</quantity>
. Head covered with light brown, grey-tipped scales, frons paler, light grey; labial palpus upcurved, palpomere 2 covered with black white-tipped scales on outer and lower surface, inner and upper surface greyish white, underside with moderate row, palpomere 3 approximately 1/2 as long as and as wide as palpomere 2, black white-tipped at basal 1/2 and grey brown-tipped with sparse black scales in distal half, acute, scape black, flagellomeres light brown with dark ring; thorax and tegulae concolourous with head, forewing light grey, veins densely mottled with light brown and mixed with black, cilia greyish brown; hindwing grey with dark veins, cilia grey. Abdomen greyish brown, grey on underside.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,294,321]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[392,559,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 118–122" captionStartId="61.[151,264,1891,1915]" captionTargetBox="[208,1378,193,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-16@61.[195,1392,181,1866]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 118–122. Scrobipalpa spp., male genitalia.118–120. S. typica sp. nov., PT. 118. South Africa, P.K. le Roux Dam (gen. slide 96/17, OB). 119. Namibia, Karasberge (gen. slide 491/14, OB). 120. South Africa, Louis Trichardt (gen. slide 133/17, OB). 121, 122. S. staudei sp. nov., South Africa, Magaliesburg. 121. PT (gen. slide 184/20, OB). 122. HT (gen. slide 3/19, OB)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5712574" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5712574/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Figs 121, 122</figureCitation>
). Uncus subrectangular, slightly longer than wide, posterior margin weakly rounded; gnathos slender, short, weakly curved; culcitula large, longer than uncus; tegumen weakly narrowed distally, anteromedial emargination broadly rounded, extending to about 1/2 length of tegumen; valva slender, weakly sinuate, apex broadened, extending to top of uncus; sacculus approximately 1.5 times as broad as and 1/4 length of valva, weakly turned inwards, with pointed tip, vinculum twice as long as wide, posterior margin with moderately broad, V-shaped medial emargination, vincular process short, with outwardly curved pointed tip; saccus broad, nearly uniform in width, apex triangular, extending well beyond top of pedunculus; phallus straight, distal portion weakly narrowed, apical hook slender, caecum weakly inflated, 1/2 as long as phallus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,151,789]" box="[199,528,582,609]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,403,582,609]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Female genitalia.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,618,644]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Biology.</emphasis>
Larvae were observed feeding on 
<taxonomicName box="[676,920,619,645]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Lopholaena" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="coriifolia">
<emphasis box="[676,920,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Lopholaena coriifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[934,1060,619,645]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
) in February, with pupation on 23 February and 4 March. Adults emerged on 12, 17 and 27 March (
<bibRefCitation author="Staude, H. S. &amp; Maclean, M. &amp; Mecenero, S. &amp; Pretorius, R. J. &amp; Oberprieler, R. G. &amp; Van Noort, S. &amp; Sharp, A. &amp; Sharp, I. &amp; Balona, J. &amp; Bradley, S. &amp; Brink, M. &amp; Morton, A. S. &amp; Botha, M. J. &amp; Collins, S. C. &amp; Grobler, Q. &amp; Edge, D. A. &amp; Williams, M. C. &amp; Sihvonen, P." box="[880,1129,654,681]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 380" refId="ref54938" refString="Staude, H. S., Maclean, M., Mecenero, S., Pretorius, R. J., Oberprieler, R. G., Van Noort, S., Sharp, A., Sharp, I., Balona, J., Bradley, S., Brink, M., Morton, A. S., Botha, M. J., Collins, S. C., Grobler, Q., Edge, D. A., Williams, M. C. &amp; Sihvonen, P. (2020) An overview of Lepidoptera-host-parasitoid associations for southern Africa, including an illustrated report on 2 370 African Lepidoptera-host and 119 parasitoid-Lepidoptera associations. Metamorphosis, 31 (3), 1 - 380." type="journal article" year="2020">
Staude 
<emphasis box="[965,1014,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">et al</emphasis>
. 2020: 58
</bibRefCitation>
, as 
<taxonomicName box="[1171,1348,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Scrobipalpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1171,1307,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Scrobipalpa</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
